–1409","1345–1410":"1345–1410","1359–1418":"1359–1418","1368–Male":"1368–Overleden","1369–1418":"1369–1418","–1401":"–1401","–Female":"Overleden","before November 1369":"vóór november 1369","Bef 29 September 1359":"vóór 29 september 1359","1290":"1290","1359":"1359","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1259":"1259","1368":"1368","1401":"1401","1345":"1345","1334":"1334","1410":"1410","1409":"1409","1418":"1418","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England","Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England"},"en":{"–before November 1369":"–before November 1369","–1369":"–1369","1334–1409":"1334–1409","1345–1410":"1345–1410","1359–1418":"1359–1418","1368–Male":"1368–Deceased","1369–1418":"1369–1418","–1401":"–1401","–Female":"Deceased","before November 1369":"before November 1369","Bef 29 September 1359":"before 29 September 1359","1290":"1290","1359":"1359","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1259":"1259","1368":"1368","1401":"1401","1345":"1345","1334":"1334","1410":"1410","1409":"1409","1418":"1418","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England","Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Strange","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Gloucestershire): nickname for a newcomer to a district, from Middle English <i>strange</i> ‘foreign’ (Old French <i>estrange</i>, Latin <i>extraneus</i>, from <i>extra</i> ‘outside’).","Irish (Antrim): this name is also common in Ireland, where, in addition to its English etymology, it may represent an Anglicized form of any of several Irish names containing the element <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’, e.g.   Doyle  ,   Gallagher  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stranger","meanings":["English: nickname for a newcomer to an area, from Middle English <i>stra(u)nger(e)</i> ‘stranger, foreigner’ (Old French <i>estrangier</i>). Compare   Strange  ."]},{"name":"Doyle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Sean, Kieran, Seamus, Aileen, Dermot, Liam, Niall, Brennan, Brigid, Conal, Conan, Donal.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Dubhghaill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Dubhghall</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>dubh</i> ‘black’ + <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’. This was used as a byname for Scandinavians, in particular to distinguish the darker-haired Danes from fair-haired Norwegians. Compare   McDougall  ,   McDowell  ."]},{"name":"Lestrange","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Strange   1 with fused Old French definite article <i>le</i>.","Irish: in Ireland, adopted for <b>Mac Conchoigchríche</b> ‘son of <i>Cúchoigcriche</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘hound of the borderland’. <i>Lestrange</i> was adopted for <b>Mac Conchoigchríche</b> probably due to the presence of a prominent family of Lestrange, of similar meaning, who settled in the counties of Westmeath and Offaly in the 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":65,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":22